			<div class="date">
				<span class="month"><a href="http://joshuastarlight.tumblr.com/post/6461409328/look-man-wed-probably-most-of-us-agree-that">Jun</a></span>
				<span class="day"><a href="http://joshuastarlight.tumblr.com/post/6461409328/look-man-wed-probably-most-of-us-agree-that">12</a></span>
			</div> <!-- .date -->
			
			

			

			
		
			
			<div class="post post-quote">
				<p class="quote">Look man, we’d probably most of us agree that these are dark times, and stupid ones, but do we need fiction that does nothing but dramatize how dark and stupid everything is? In dark times, the definition of good art would seem to be art that locates and applies CPR to those elements of what’s human and magical that still lives and glow despite the times’ darkness. Really good fiction could have as dark a worldview as it wished, but it’d find a way both to depict this world and to illuminate the possibilities for being alive and human in it.</p>
				<p class="source">- David Foster Wallace (via <a href="http://ilikeitshows.tumblr.com/" target="_blank">ilikeitshows</a>)</p>
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
		
			
			
			
				
				<div class="postmeta">
					
					
					<p class="reblogged"><a href="http://joshuastarlight.tumblr.com/post/6461409328/look-man-wed-probably-most-of-us-agree-that">Reblogged 3 years ago</a> from <a href="http://blog.maxistentialism.com/post/6461338938/look-man-wed-probably-most-of-us-agree-that">maxistentialist</a></p>
					

					
